# OAuth MCPs — manual re-auth per machine

Copy this file to `oauth-mcps.md` (strip `.example`) and edit it with the MCPs you use.

HTTP MCPs that authenticate via OAuth **cannot be synced through Syncthing** — the credentials are short-lived refresh tokens + session cookies + device verification. By OAuth design, you have to re-authenticate **per machine, once**.

## OAuth MCPs used by this setup

<!-- Edit to match the MCPs you register via Claude Code -->

| MCP | URL | Login via |
|-----|-----|-----------|
| Gmail | `https://gmail.mcp.claude.com/mcp` | Google account |
| Google Drive | `https://drivemcp.googleapis.com/mcp/v1` | Google account |
| Google Calendar | `https://gcal.mcp.claude.com/mcp` | Google account |
| Notion | `https://mcp.notion.com/mcp` | Notion account |
| Hugging Face | `https://huggingface.co/mcp?login&gradio=none` | HF account |

## Re-auth flow on a new machine

1. Open `claude` in any project on the new machine.
2. Use any tool that depends on one of the MCPs above (e.g. "read today's emails" → Gmail). Claude Code detects the MCP needs auth.
3. Claude Code prints an OAuth URL. Open it in a browser on the SAME machine.
4. Log in with the right account → redirect to the callback → token saved locally.
5. Repeat for every MCP you want available.

Estimated time: ~5 minutes for the 5 MCPs listed. Once per machine.

## Why can't this be automated?

- OAuth tokens live in `~/.claude/.credentials.json` (600 perms). Technically `scp`-able, but:
  - Many providers (Google, Notion) invalidate the token if the device fingerprint changes.
  - MFA/2FA can ask for interactive confirmation even after copying.
  - A leak or corrupted file forces revocation across ALL accounts.
- Best practice: accept the one-off manual re-auth per machine. It's O(machines), not O(sessions).

## Check the state

```bash
claude mcp list | grep -E "claude\.ai"
```

Expected output after full re-auth:
```
claude.ai Gmail: https://... - ✓ Connected
claude.ai Google Drive: https://... - ✓ Connected
...
```

If you see `! Needs authentication`, repeat the flow for that specific MCP.
